{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774458223,"nonce":"BCcHU2rdSaqE3SCxK4sk1fe/YOo=","title":"Part 2 analysis: adversary strategy verification","message":"Umbrella: 0af472c (Part 2)\n\n**Motivation:** When training with adversarial perturbations (PAI-ASF), the adversary learns a perturbation strategy that should exploit the controller weaknesses. Verifying what strategy the adversary converges to is essential for interpreting the trained networks: does the adversary find curl fields? Divergent fields? Time-varying strategies? Does it exploit SISU-specific vulnerabilities?\n\n**Approach:**\n1. Extract the learned adversary parameters (perturbation field) from trained models across different SISU levels and training conditions.\n2. Decompose the adversary force field into canonical components: curl (rotational), divergent (compressive/expansive), and uniform (translational). This can be done via Helmholtz decomposition or by fitting to a basis of force field types.\n3. Analyze how the adversary strategy varies with SISU: does the adversary use different perturbations when SISU signals high vs low perturbation likelihood?\n4. Compare adversary strategy across training methods (standard backprop vs CVaR vs APT) to understand how the training objective shapes the adversary.\n5. Visualize the force fields as vector plots in effector space, overlaid with reaching trajectories.\n\n**Status:** No module exists yet. This is a new analysis specific to the Part 2.5 adversarial training experiments. Requires access to adversary model parameters, which are stored alongside the controller models.\n\n**Cross-references:**\n- Part 2.5 experiment issues: c05998e, e81f491\n- Related to training method comparison: 753508c, a3edc0c","files":null}]}